https://neetcode.io/problems/search-in-rotated-sorted-array-ii/question

why to add duplciates logic here?
nums = [1, 0, 1, 1, 1]
target = 0


ğŸ‘‰ Problem:
The left side [1, 0, 1] was not actually sorted, but because of duplicates (1 1 1), the algorithm mistakenly thinks it is.

The target 0 was in the left half â€” but it just got discarded.

Eventually, the search fails âŒ.

â€œI cannot determine which half is sorted because duplicates hide the rotation.â€

So instead of making a wrong binary decision, we:

shrink the search space safely

keep the target range intact



class Solution {
public:
    bool search(vector<int>& nums, int target) 
    {
        int n=nums.size();
        int l=0,r=n-1;

        while(l<=r)
        {
            int mid=(r-l)/2+l;
            if(nums[mid]==target) return true;

            //avoid duplicates
            if(nums[l]==nums[mid] && nums[mid]==nums[r])
            {
                l++;
                r--;
                continue;
            }

            //check if left is sorted
            if(nums[l]<=nums[mid])
            {
                if(target>=nums[l] && target<=nums[mid])
                {
                    r = mid-1;
                }
                else
                {
                    l = mid+1;
                }
            }
            else //right sorted
            {
                if(target>=nums[mid] && target<=nums[r])
                {
                    l = mid+1;
                }
                else
                {
                    r = mid-1;
                }
            }
        }
        return false;
    }
};
